{{Violence against Muslims in India}}
{{Terrorist attacks in India (since 2001)}}
From the night of 1 May 2014 until the early morning hours of 3 May a series of attacks occurred on the [[Bengali Muslims]] in [[Assam]], a north-eastern state of India.  The perpetrator is unknown, but is suspected to be the [[National Democratic Front of Bodoland]] of [[I K Songbijit|Songbijit]] faction.<ref name="ie1" /><ref name="fplive">{{cite web|url=http://www.firstpost.com/india/assam-live-30-including-children-killed-in-fresh-attacks-1506649.html|title=Assam live: 30, including children, killed in fresh attacks|work=Firstpost|date=3 May 2014|accessdate=3 May 2014}}</ref> Speculated to be revenge for not voting for the National Democratic Front in the [[2014 Indian general election|Lok Sabha elections]],<ref name="toi1" /> the death toll reached 32.<ref name="dna1">{{cite news | url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-death-toll-up-to-32-in-assam-1984510 | title=Death toll up to 32 in Assam | work=DNA | date=3 May 2014 | accessdate=4 May 2014}}</ref>

==Background==
The [[Bodo people|Bodos]] are an indigenous community in [[Assam]] state of India. It is about 10% its population of 44 million people. [[Insurgency in Northeast India]] is ongoing for decades involving several rebel groups. [[2012 Assam violence|In 2012, violence]] between Bodo tribal people and Muslims resulted in 108 deaths fueled by a Assam Police Constable  Mohibur Islam alisa Ratul.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/guwahati/Assam-cop-triggered-Bodoland-riots-CBI/articleshow/45377734.cms|title=Assam cop triggered Bodoland riots: CBI - Times of India|work=The Times of India|access-date=2018-09-24}}</ref> In India, [[2014 Indian general election|Loksabha election]] is ongoing which will conclude its last phase on 12 May and the results will be declared on 16 May.<ref name=ht>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/police-kill-3-assam-sectarian-violence-suspects-arrest-8/article1-1215394.aspx|title =Police kill 3 Assam sectarian violence suspects, arrest 8 forest guards|work =Hindustan Times |date=4 May 2014}}</ref>

==Attacks==
Around 07:30 PM IST on 1 May, insurgents raided the [[Narsingbari]] village of [[Baksa district|Baksa]] district opening fire on a house, killing three women and injuring two others. The attackers had arrived on bicycles. On early hours of 2 May, another group of insurgents opened fire at three houses in [[Balapara]] village of [[Kokrajhar]] district, killing seven people. On the evening of the same day, another group killed 12 people and burnt down 30 thatched houses near [[Baksa district|Baksa]]'s [[Manas National Park]].<ref name="toi1" />

On 3 May, four suspected insurgents attacked police in the forest near Tejpur. Police fired in retaliation which killed two while two other escaped. Police also killed one more suspect in Udalguri district from whom they recovered a revolver and a hand grenade.<ref name=ht/>

==Investigation==
Police arrested 22 people along with eight forest guards to investigate their involvement.<ref name=ht/> The Assam government has decided to hand over the probe to [[National Investigation Agency]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Assam Riots 2014: Assam Government hands over Case to NIA|url=http://news.biharprabha.com/2014/05/assam-riots-2014-assam-government-hands-over-case-to-nia/|work=IANS|publisher=news.biharprabha.com|accessdate=4 May 2014}}</ref>

==Aftermath==

===Security measures===
Due to the attack, several Muslims from [[Duramari]] and [[Dotoma]] region of [[Kokrajhar]] district fled their houses. [[Bodoland Territorial Council]] chief [[Hagrama Mohilary]] pacified the panicked people and promised them of security.<ref name="toi1" /> Curfew was clamped in Kokrajhar, Baksa and [[Chirang district|Chirang]] districts and shoot-on-sight orders have been issued in Kokrajhar and Baksa.<ref name="ie1" />

Army stages out flag marches in sensitive areas of Kokrajhar and Baksa districts. Ten additional companies of [[Central Reserve Police Force]] were moved to the two districts. Strong action against National Democratic Font has been initiated by the home ministry of India.<ref name="toi1" />

Union Home Ministry deployed 43 companies of the [[Central Armed Police Forces]] while Defense ministry also deployed 15 columns of the Army comprising approximately 1,500 soldiers.<ref>{{cite web|title=Assam violence act of certain group cadres: Sushilkumar Shinde |url=http://news.biharprabha.com/2014/05/assam-violence-act-of-certain-group-cadres-sushilkumar-shinde/|work=IANS|publisher=news.biharprabha.com|accessdate=4 May 2014}}</ref>

===Responses===
Chief minister of Assam, [[Tarun Gogoi]] reviewed the situation with top government officials. The opposition political parties blamed the Gogoi-led government in failing to protect lives despite intelligence alerts.<ref name="ie1" />

Prime Minister of India, [[Manmohan Singh]] condemned the attack and termed it as a cowardly attempt to spread fear and terror.<ref>{{cite web|title=Prime Minister condemns Assam attacks as toll rises to 28|url=http://news.biharprabha.com/2014/05/prime-minister-condemns-assam-attacks-as-toll-rises-to-28/|work=IANS|publisher=news.biharprabha.com|accessdate=4 May 2014}}</ref>

In a statement, the National Democratic Front of Bodoland (Songbijit) denied their involvement in the attack and claimed it was conspiracy by the state government to create communal friction between Bodos and Muslims.<ref name="bst1" /><ref name="dna3">{{cite news | url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-ndfb-denies-involvement-in-violence-1984798| title=NDFB denies involvement in violence| work=DNA | date=4 May 2014 | accessdate=4 May 2014}}</ref>

Relatives of the killed urged the Chief minister [[Tarun Gogoi]] to provide affirmation of security for their lives and stalled the last rites for those dead. They also complained of pressure from local authorities to conduct funeral rites for the killed.<ref name="dna2">{{cite news | url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-locals-in-violence-hit-assam-refuse-to-bury-dead-till-tarun-gogoi-visits-them-1984822| title=Locals in violence-hit Assam refuse to bury dead till Tarun Gogoi visits them| work=DNA | date=4 May 2014 | accessdate=4 May 2014}}</ref>

